<ReaderLayout
  title="Retro Computing Archaeology"
  description="Old machines, new lessons. Digging through decades of code."
  updated="February 2026"
  tags={['retro', 'computing', 'history', 'assembly']}
>
  <p>
    I spend too much time reading old assembly listings. There's something about
    fitting a program into 4KB of memory that modern development has lost.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Old Code Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Modern software is bloated. An app that displays text can weigh 100MB+.
    The Apollo guidance computer had 72KB of ROM. It flew us to the moon.
  </p>

  <p>
    Not everything old is worth preserving. But understanding how people solved
    hard problems with tiny resources teaches you something you can't get from
    reading modern tutorials.
  </p>

  <h2>🖥️ Machines Worth Knowing</h2>

  <h3> Commodore 64 (1982)</h3>
  <p>
    64KB of RAM. 0.985 MHz CPU. Best-selling computer ever.
    <a href="https://www.c64os.com">The community is still incredibly active.</a>
  </p>

  <h3> Apple II (1977)</h3>
  <p>
    Wozniak's masterpiece. Elegant hardware design. The first computer
    many programmers learned on.
  </p>

  <h3> DEC PDP-11 (1970)</h3>
  <p>
    The architecture that inspired C. Unix was written here.
    Understanding this helps you understand why C works the way it does.
  </p>

  <h3> IBM System/370 (1970)</h3>
  <p>
    Mainframes are still everywhere. COBOL runs on them. Someone has to
    maintain that code. Might as well understand it.
  </p>

  <h2>📜 Languages Worth Learning</h2>

  <h3>Assembly (6502, Z80, 8086)</h3>
  <p>
    You don't need to write it. You need to be able to read it.
    <a href="https://skilldrick.github.io/easy6502/">Easy 6502</a> is a great start.
  </p>

  <h3>Forth</h3>
  <p>
    Stack-based, minimal, weird. Used in spacecraft and hearing aids.
    <a href="https://github.com/nicholashh/joy-forth">Joy Forth</a> is a modern take.
  </p>

  <h3>Lisp</h3>
  <p>
    John McCarthy wrote the original paper in 1958. It's still relevant.
    <a href="https://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=3385">The roots of everything are here.</a>
  </p>

  <h2>🔧 Tools I Use</h2>

  <div class="resource-card">
    <div class="resource-icon">🔧</div>
    <div class="resource-info">
      <div class="resource-title">PCem</div>
      <div class="resource-desc">PC emulator. Runs Windows 95 at real speed. Painfully accurate.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="resource-card">
    <div class="resource-icon">🔧</div>
    <div class="resource-info">
